100
00:03:51,420 --> 00:03:54,150
Step three, become a producer.

101
00:03:54,150 --> 00:03:57,270
The truth is, for the world to
go round, we need consumers.

102
00:03:57,270 --> 00:03:59,670
People need to watch
mindless entertainment,

103
00:03:59,670 --> 00:04:02,100
buy products and fall into bad debt

104
00:04:02,100 --> 00:04:04,590
so that 1% can reap the rewards.

105
00:04:04,590 --> 00:04:06,060
I know it sounds obvious,

106
00:04:06,060 --> 00:04:07,620
but if you created something

107
00:04:07,620 --> 00:04:08,970
and there was no one to buy it

108
00:04:08,970 --> 00:04:10,440
then you couldn't become rich.

109
00:04:10,440 --> 00:04:13,620
It's so easy for us all
to fall into consumer mode

110
00:04:13,620 --> 00:04:15,780
as it's baked into our DNA.

111
00:04:15,780 --> 00:04:18,150
We just wanna relax, watch TV

112
00:04:18,150 --> 00:04:19,680
and buy the latest products.

113
00:04:19,680 --> 00:04:21,030
Some people think you should cut

114
00:04:21,030 --> 00:04:23,640
all of the consumer
habits out of your life

115
00:04:23,640 --> 00:04:24,960
but to be honest with you,

116
00:04:24,960 --> 00:04:27,360
I find a whole monk mode movement

117
00:04:27,360 --> 00:04:29,310
a bit unrealistic and cringey.

118
00:04:29,310 --> 00:04:32,250
Monk mode consists of basic rules such as

119
00:04:32,250 --> 00:04:34,740
at least 10 minutes of daily meditation,

120
00:04:34,740 --> 00:04:36,300
no drugs or alcohol

121
00:04:36,300 --> 00:04:38,910
and at least 30 minutes of daily exercise.

122
00:04:38,910 --> 00:04:41,820
Honestly, I've never put
rules like this on myself.

123
00:04:41,820 --> 00:04:44,130
It would've just sucked
all the joy out of life.

124
00:04:44,130 --> 00:04:47,010
However, I do agree with the principle.

125
00:04:47,010 --> 00:04:49,590
I like to think of it as a sliding scale

126
00:04:49,590 --> 00:04:52,980
with producer on one end
and consumer on the other.

127
00:04:52,980 --> 00:04:55,620
I've always aimed to slide
my scale more towards

128
00:04:55,620 --> 00:04:57,390
the producer end of the spectrum.

129
00:04:57,390 --> 00:04:59,430
When I was younger, I gave up the things

130
00:04:59,430 --> 00:05:00,930
I wasn't too worried about,

131
00:05:00,930 --> 00:05:03,930
such as parties with people
I wasn't that close to.

132
00:05:03,930 --> 00:05:07,170
Instead, I'd use that time to
work on my product designs.

133
00:05:07,170 --> 00:05:09,000
Even if you're able to push your scale

134
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:11,760
just a little bit
towards the producer end,

135
00:05:11,760 --> 00:05:14,190
then you will get ahead of most people

136
00:05:14,190 --> 00:05:16,320
as they aren't even aware
they go through life

137
00:05:16,320 --> 00:05:17,880
fully on consumer mode.

138
00:05:17,880 --> 00:05:21,420
Step four, become better
at asking questions.

139
00:05:21,420 --> 00:05:24,510
Lots of videos like this
will say find a mentor.

140
00:05:24,510 --> 00:05:28,470
However, they're very vague
about how to actually do that.

141
00:05:28,470 --> 00:05:30,870
The secret lies in the questions you ask.

142
00:05:30,870 --> 00:05:33,810
When I was a kid, I loved model airplanes.

143
00:05:33,810 --> 00:05:35,910
I didn't stop asking my dad about them,

144
00:05:35,910 --> 00:05:38,460
so he took me to a model flying club.

145
00:05:38,460 --> 00:05:41,010
The members of the club
loved my enthusiasm

146
00:05:41,010 --> 00:05:44,130
and one of them, a successful
businessman called David,

147
00:05:44,130 --> 00:05:45,300
took me under his wing.

148
00:05:45,300 --> 00:05:46,710
He would give me tips and tricks

149
00:05:46,710 --> 00:05:48,780
to make my models fly even better.

150
00:05:48,780 --> 00:05:51,330
I'd implement them and
then he'd give me even more

151
00:05:51,330 --> 00:05:52,740
the following week.

152
00:05:52,740 --> 00:05:56,520
As I got older his advice slowly
shifted into business tips,

153
00:05:56,520 --> 00:05:58,350
and i applied the same principles

154
00:05:58,350 --> 00:06:00,720
of listening and taking action.

155
00:06:00,720 --> 00:06:03,000
Right, there's something I wanna clear up.

156
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:06,120
There is such a thing as a bad question.

157
00:06:06,120 --> 00:06:08,730
Anyone that says otherwise is mistaken.

158
00:06:08,730 --> 00:06:10,710
Take this question for example,

159
00:06:10,710 --> 00:06:13,260
can I ask you for some advice?

160
00:06:13,260 --> 00:06:16,620
My Instagram messages are
fuller questions like this

161
00:06:16,620 --> 00:06:18,600
and they never get a reply.

162
00:06:18,600 --> 00:06:19,433
Here's why.

163
00:06:19,433 --> 00:06:22,410
When you are messaging
an extremely busy person

164
00:06:22,410 --> 00:06:25,080
the last thing you want to do
is create more work for them.

165
00:06:25,080 --> 00:06:27,780
If I was to reply to all those messages

166
00:06:27,780 --> 00:06:30,600
then I'll start hundreds
of new conversations.

167
00:06:30,600 --> 00:06:33,030
I'll then have to follow
up after they've replied

168
00:06:33,030 --> 00:06:34,290
with their actual question.

169
00:06:34,290 --> 00:06:36,630
So I've made a rule to
only answer the people

170
00:06:36,630 --> 00:06:38,820
that ask clear and concise questions.

171
00:06:38,820 --> 00:06:40,980
I suspect a lot of other successful people

172
00:06:40,980 --> 00:06:44,190
have similar rules, so the
quality of the questions you ask

173
00:06:44,190 --> 00:06:46,200
will determine whether
or not they help you.

174
00:06:46,200 --> 00:06:48,420
On top of this, if you
ask someone for advice

175
00:06:48,420 --> 00:06:49,830
and then don't take action,

176
00:06:49,830 --> 00:06:51,570
the next time you need advice

177
00:06:51,570 --> 00:06:52,920
they aren't gonna waste their time.

178
00:06:52,920 --> 00:06:56,010
However, be careful as
there's a lot of fake mentors

179
00:06:56,010 --> 00:06:59,340
and gurus out there, so
you need to be very careful

180
00:06:59,340 --> 00:07:01,200
who you take advice from.

181
00:07:01,200 --> 00:07:04,380
Not everyone has your
best interests at heart.

182
00:07:04,380 --> 00:07:07,560
Just remember, a fake mentor
doesn't have experience

183
00:07:07,560 --> 00:07:10,590
in doing what they teach, a real one does.

184
00:07:10,590 --> 00:07:13,800
Step five, become immune to net worth.

185
00:07:13,800 --> 00:07:15,510
Look, I'm just gonna say it,

186
00:07:15,510 --> 00:07:17,700
net worth means nothing.

187
00:07:17,700 --> 00:07:19,140
Bear with me on this one.

188
00:07:19,140 --> 00:07:21,510
In my opinion, getting
ahead of everyone else

189
00:07:21,510 --> 00:07:23,490
isn't just to do with how rich you are.

190
00:07:23,490 --> 00:07:25,500
It's about the skills, the knowledge

191
00:07:25,500 --> 00:07:27,210
and the confidence you acquire

192
00:07:27,210 --> 00:07:28,680
while you are building your empire.

193
00:07:28,680 --> 00:07:30,360
Someone could have bought Shiba Inu

194
00:07:30,360 --> 00:07:33,690
in the last crypto ball run
and cashed out billions.

195
00:07:33,690 --> 00:07:35,940
This doesn't mean they
know anything useful

196
00:07:35,940 --> 00:07:38,580
and how to actually
replicate that success.

197
00:07:38,580 --> 00:07:40,710
The exact same goes for lottery winners.

198
00:07:40,710 --> 00:07:44,160
They often lose all the
money they won very rapidly,

199
00:07:44,160 --> 00:07:46,680
as they became rich because of a shortcut,

200
00:07:46,680 --> 00:07:48,480
not the skills that they developed.

201
00:07:48,480 --> 00:07:51,300
Some industries are much
tougher than others,

202
00:07:51,300 --> 00:07:55,500
so in many cases, an
entrepreneur worth of $10 million

203
00:07:55,500 --> 00:07:57,960
might actually be a better businessman

204
00:07:57,960 --> 00:07:59,910
than a Silicon Valley tech entrepreneur

205
00:07:59,910 --> 00:08:01,200
worth 100 million.

206
00:08:01,200 --> 00:08:03,930
This is why you really
shouldn't be measuring yourself

207
00:08:03,930 --> 00:08:05,280
based on net worth.

208
00:08:05,280 --> 00:08:06,810
I understand why people do it.

209
00:08:06,810 --> 00:08:09,090
It's an easy way to compare success.

210
00:08:09,090 --> 00:08:12,744
However, there is much more to
be in ahead of everyone else

211
00:08:12,744 --> 00:08:14,742
than the size of your bank account.

212
00:08:14,742 --> 00:08:17,010
Step six, become less awkward with money.

213
00:08:17,010 --> 00:08:20,340
Every dollar that you spend,
someone else is earning.

214
00:08:20,340 --> 00:08:23,070
Every building you see as
you drive down the street

215
00:08:23,070 --> 00:08:24,810
someone else owns.

216
00:08:24,810 --> 00:08:26,100
The amount of money out there

217
00:08:26,100 --> 00:08:28,170
waiting to be grabbed would shock you.

218
00:08:28,170 --> 00:08:30,060
Believing that money is hard to make

219
00:08:30,060 --> 00:08:32,820
or that there's a very limited supply

220
00:08:32,820 --> 00:08:35,160
is what keeps so many people trapped.

221
00:08:35,160 --> 00:08:36,660
I was talking with an author called

222
00:08:36,660 --> 00:08:38,490
Daniel Priestley the other day,

223
00:08:38,490 --> 00:08:40,050
and he mentioned that his mentor

224
00:08:40,050 --> 00:08:42,570
actually made him carry around $1,000

225
00:08:42,570 --> 00:08:44,220
in his pocket when he was younger.

226
00:08:44,220 --> 00:08:46,710
This might sound dangerous,
but the reason behind it

227
00:08:46,710 --> 00:08:50,250
was to make Daniel think
of $1,000 as pocket change,

228
00:08:50,250 --> 00:08:51,870
not his entire net worth.

229
00:08:51,870 --> 00:08:53,550
Becoming more comfortable with money

230
00:08:53,550 --> 00:08:56,520
will help you ask for
raises, start a side hustle,

231
00:08:56,520 --> 00:08:58,410
or even a full blown business.

232
00:08:58,410 --> 00:09:01,200
When my son started his
first videography business

233
00:09:01,200 --> 00:09:03,270
I asked him how much he was gonna charge

234
00:09:03,270 --> 00:09:07,200
and he told me $100 per
day, and I just laughed.

235
00:09:07,200 --> 00:09:09,210
We actually had quite a
big argument over that

236
00:09:09,210 --> 00:09:12,000
and maybe my response was a bit harsh.

237
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:15,390
The issue is, that he
thought that $100 was a lot,

238
00:09:15,390 --> 00:09:18,300
because he was thinking
about how he spends money,

239
00:09:18,300 --> 00:09:20,100
not how business operates.

240
00:09:20,100 --> 00:09:22,890
Long story short, I
convinced him to charge

241
00:09:22,890 --> 00:09:24,960
more than $200 per day,

242
00:09:24,960 --> 00:09:29,490
and now he takes consultations
for more than $5,000 a day,

243
00:09:29,490 --> 00:09:31,080
something that he wouldn't have been able

244
00:09:31,080 --> 00:09:33,150
to even comprehend five years ago.

245
00:09:33,150 --> 00:09:35,220
The other thing that happens
when you start to realize

246
00:09:35,220 --> 00:09:36,810
that money is everywhere,

247
00:09:36,810 --> 00:09:39,270
is you actually become
less afraid of giving,

248
00:09:39,270 --> 00:09:42,600
and this is the real
secret of getting rich.

249
00:09:42,600 --> 00:09:44,580
You need to give far more value

250
00:09:44,580 --> 00:09:46,980
to other people than you take in return.

251
00:09:46,980 --> 00:09:50,160
If you provide value, then
the money will follow.

252
00:09:50,160 --> 00:09:52,470
The size of your income
will also be determined

253
00:09:52,470 --> 00:09:54,240
by the problems you solve.

254
00:09:54,240 --> 00:09:57,930
So if you wanna make big
money, solve big problems.

255
00:09:57,930 --> 00:10:01,350
Look, if we go back to
my flying days as a pilot

256
00:10:01,350 --> 00:10:04,770
a one degree difference in
the trajectory of a flight

257
00:10:04,770 --> 00:10:07,740
will put the plane in a
